{{Zitat|On Akhit IV 25, on this day of laying onions, on the night of the Goddess Festival and at the {{ill|morning light|ja|朝の光|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/morning light|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} of Akhit IV 26, when one celebrates the Festival of Sokar in its annual feast.|Rites of celebration in the tomb of Khabekhenet (TT2)<ref>Siegfried Schott: ''Altägyptische Festdaten''. Mainz et al. 1950, pp. 91–92.</ref>}}

The Sokar Festival ended on Akhit IV 30 with the symbolic raising of the [[:en:Djed|Djed pillar]], which the king began at dawn with the help of the priests shortly before [[:en:Sunrise|sunrise]], completing it with the first rays of the [[Season of the Emergence]] I 1 sun. This act symbolized the resurrection of the god Sokar and the mythological association with the king, who was to receive renewed strength for the years of reign to come through this ritual.<ref>Maria Carmela Betrò: ''Heilige Zeichen. 580 Ägyptische Hieroglyphen. Die ganze Welt der Pharaonen wird verständlich und lebendig.'' Marix, Wiesbaden 2004, ISBN 3-937715-33-9, p. 209.</ref>

By the {{ill|Greco-Roman Egypt|ja|ギリシア・ローマ時代のエジプト|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Greco-Roman Egypt|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, the "{{ill|Festival of the Beating of the Earth|ja|地面をたたく祭り|qq=|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Festival of the Beating of the Earth|de|Fest_der_aufgehackten_Erde|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}" within the [[:en:Koiak|Ka-her-ka]]-Isis rituals replaced the Sokar celebrations.

